Math 421 - Midterm

Instruction

The midterm has two components: the Rmarkdown notebook (html) and the presentation. We will do the presentation in class. Post both the notebook and the presentation on your Github page.

The notebook: The notebook should be created using rmarkdown or Quarto (like other assignments). The notebook should have a title.

The Presentation: Present your results in 5-10 minutes. To make the presentation using Rmarkdown, do the follows:

- In Rstudio -> File -> New File -> R markdown

- In the left panel, click to Presentation -> Click OK

- Now you have an Rmarkdown that can be knitted to be a html presentation

  • You can also use the Rmd templates of the class slides.

  • You can also use Quarto to create the presentation: In Rstudio -> File -> New File -> Quarto Presentation

  • You do not need to rerun all the codes for the presentation. For example, to show the model comparison, you just need to show the image of the model comparison instead of running all the models again.

  • To inset an image in a slide, use ![](image.png)

  • To scale images, you can use ![](image.png){width="60%"} or follow these below instructions.

    • https://bookdown.org/yihui/rmarkdown-cookbook/figure-size.html

    • http://zevross.com/blog/2017/06/19/tips-and-tricks-for-working-with-images-and-figures-in-r-markdown-documents/

  • To turn off message and warning of a code cell, use: {r, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE} for the cell.

What to present:

  • Present Part 2 - Visualization

  • Present Question Question 4, 5 and 6 in Part 3.

  • Present any errors/challenges you run into and how you fix/overcome them.

    is_missing <- function(x) {
  if (is.character(x)) is.na(x) | str_trim(x) == "" else is.na(x)
}

  11. Create a season (Spring, Summer, Fall, Winter) variable. Calculate the length of stays by season. Which season has the longest length of stays on average?

    df18_season <- df18_nomissvars %>%
  mutate(
    season = case_when(
      moa %in% c(3,4,5) ~ "Spring",
      moa %in% c(6,7,8) ~ "Summer",
      moa %in% c(9,10,11) ~ "Fall",
      moa %in% c(12,1,2) ~ "Winter",
      TRUE ~ NA_character_
    )
  )

los_by_season <- df18_season %>%

Continue with the data from part I.

  1. Provides at least 10 meaningful plots. Comments on the plots. All plots should have title, caption, appropriate labels on x and y-axis

  2. Make an animation plot.

    library(dplyr)
library(stringr)
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)
library(gganimate)

df_viz <- df18 %>%
  filter(yod == 18) %>%
  select(any_of(c("moa","sex","age","los","provider","tot","raceethn","admtype"))) %>%
  mutate(
    moa = as.integer(moa),
    sex = factor(sex),
    age = as.numeric(age),
    los = as.numeric(los),
    tot = as.numeric(tot),
    provider = factor(provider)
  )

p1 <- ggplot(df_viz, aes(x = factor(moa))) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Admissions by Month (2018)", x = "Month of Admission (moa)", y = "Number of Patients",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p2 <- ggplot(df_viz, aes(x = factor(moa), fill = sex)) +
  geom_bar() +
  labs(title = "Admissions by Month by Sex", x = "Month of Admission (moa)", y = "Number of Patients", fill = "Sex",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p3 <- ggplot(df_viz, aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 30) +
  labs(title = "Age Distribution", x = "Age", y = "Count",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p4 <- ggplot(df_viz, aes(x = factor(moa), y = age)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Age by Admission Month", x = "Month of Admission (moa)", y = "Age",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p5 <- ggplot(df_viz, aes(x = factor(moa), y = los)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Length of Stay by Month", x = "Month of Admission (moa)", y = "Length of Stay (los)",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p6 <- df_viz %>%
  group_by(provider) %>%
  summarize(total_charge = sum(tot, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%
  slice_max(total_charge, n = 15, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(provider, total_charge), y = total_charge)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = dollar) +
  labs(title = "Top 15 Providers by Total Charge", x = "Provider", y = "Total Charge (sum of tot)",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p7 <- ggplot(df_viz, aes(x = los, y = tot)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.2) +
  labs(title = "Total Charge vs Length of Stay", x = "Length of Stay (los)", y = "Total Charge (tot)",
       caption = "Source: RI Hospital Discharge Data")

p8 <- df_viz %>%
  group_by(moa) %>%
  summarize(avg_tot = mean(tot, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop") %>%

if ("raceethn" %in% names(df_viz)) {

III. Predictive Models

Continue with the data from part I. Make sure you do not have any missing values in the data. Use the follows as the target and input variables:

Target Variable: Create the target variable taking value of

  • low if the total charge of a patient (tot) is smaller than the median of the total charge, and

  • high otherwise.

Input Variables:

  • age,sex,raceethn,provider,moa,mod,admtype,campus, los

  1. Use filter function to filter out rows where raceethn=='' or admtype==''. Make sure all the categorical variables are factor, numeric variables are numeric. Set Training : Testing Split = 10 : 90

    library(dplyr)
library(caret)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)

model_df <- df18 %>%
  select(age, sex, raceethn, provider, moa, mod, admtype, campus, los, tot) %>%
  filter(raceethn != "", admtype != "") %>%
  drop_na()

med_tot <- median(as.numeric(model_df$tot))

model_df <- model_df %>%
  mutate(
    target = ifelse(as.numeric(tot) < med_tot, "low", "high"),
    target = factor(target, levels = c("low","high")),
    age = as.numeric(age),
    los = as.numeric(los),
    moa = factor(moa),
    mod = factor(mod),
    sex = factor(sex),
    raceethn = factor(raceethn),
    provider = factor(provider),
    admtype = factor(admtype),
    campus = factor(campus)
  ) %>%
  select(-tot)

set.seed(123)
idx <- createDataPartition(model_df$target, p = 0.10, list = FALSE)
train_df <- model_df[idx, ]
test_df  <- model_df[-idx, ]

  2. Train a decision tree using rpart. Plot the decision tree. Plot the variable importance ranked by the tree.

    tree_fit <- rpart(target ~ ., data = train_df, method = "class")
rpart.plot(tree_fit)

    tree_importance <- data.frame(
  variable = names(tree_fit$variable.importance),
  importance = tree_fit$variable.importance
) %>%
  arrange(desc(importance))

  3. Using caret for this question. Set Training Control to be: Use Cross-Validation of 5 folds across all models. Train & tune at least 2 different models (i.e.two different values for method= in the train function of caret). Plot the hyper-parameter tuning plots for each model.

    ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

set.seed(123)
model_rpart <- train(
  target ~ ., data = train_df,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = ctrl,
  tuneLength = 10
)

set.seed(123)
model_knn <- train(
  target ~ ., data = train_df,
  method = "knn",
  trControl = ctrl,
  tuneLength = 15
)

plot(model_rpart)

    plot(model_knn)

  4. Plot the comparison of the models in 3.

    res <- resamples(list(DecisionTree = model_rpart, KNN = model_knn))

  5. What is your final selection for the model? Test the accuracy of your final model on the test data.

    best_model <- if (
  max(model_rpart$results$Accuracy) >= max(model_knn$results$Accuracy)
) model_rpart else model_knn

pred <- predict(best_model, test_df)
confusionMatrix(pred, test_df$target)
    ## Confusion Matrix and Statistics
##

  6. Create another target variable (binary), decide the input variables and redo 1 to 5.

    model_df2 <- df18 %>%
  select(age, sex, raceethn, provider, moa, mod, admtype, campus, los) %>%
  filter(raceethn != "", admtype != "") %>%
  drop_na()

med_los <- median(as.numeric(model_df2$los))

model_df2 <- model_df2 %>%
  mutate(
    target2 = ifelse(as.numeric(los) > med_los, "high_los", "low_los"),
    target2 = factor(target2, levels = c("low_los","high_los")),
    age = as.numeric(age),
    los = as.numeric(los),
    moa = factor(moa),
    mod = factor(mod),
    sex = factor(sex),
    raceethn = factor(raceethn),
    provider = factor(provider),
    admtype = factor(admtype),
    campus = factor(campus)
  )

set.seed(456)
idx2 <- createDataPartition(model_df2$target2, p = 0.10, list = FALSE)
train2 <- model_df2[idx2, ]
test2  <- model_df2[-idx2, ]

tree2 <- rpart(target2 ~ ., data = train2, method = "class")
rpart.plot(tree2)

    ctrl2 <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 5)

set.seed(456)
model2_rpart <- train(target2 ~ ., data = train2, method = "rpart", trControl = ctrl2, tuneLength = 10)

set.seed(456)
model2_knn <- train(target2 ~ ., data = train2, method = "knn", trControl = ctrl2, tuneLength = 15)

res2 <- resamples(list(DecisionTree = model2_rpart, KNN = model2_knn))
summary(res2)

  7. Write a paragraph to summarize the section and give your comments on the results.

Both the KNN and decision tree models were used to predict the charge level base don demographics and other variables. Length of stay, provider, admission type, and patient age showed to be the variables with high importance. The decision tree was the final model I used due to its higher accuracy. The final accuracy was 0.822. The p value was 2.2e-16, which is strong; its well below .05.
